; contingency-dsl v1.0 — Formal Grammar
;
; A context-free grammar (CFG) for declaring reinforcement contingencies.
; Non-Turing-complete. Parseable by recursive descent in O(n).
;
; LL(2) formal proof: spec/en/core/ll2-proof.md (spec/ja/core/ll2-proof.md)
;   — FIRST₁/FIRST₂/FOLLOW₂ sets, LL(2) parse table, unambiguity proof,
;     Core-Stateful preservation proof. The grammar has exactly one LL(2)
;     decision point (PosTail in compound arg_list); all others are LL(1).
;
; Reference: theory.md (Ferster & Skinner, 1957; Catania, 2013)
;
; Notation:
;   ::=    definition
;   |      alternation
;   *      zero or more
;   +      one or more
;   ?      optional
;   "x"    terminal literal
;   [...]  character class
;   --     comment

; === Top-level ===

program       ::= program_annotation* param_decl* binding* annotated_schedule

; Program-level annotations: session-wide metadata (subjects, apparatus, temporal).
; Positional scoping: any "@" before the first param_decl/binding/schedule is
; a program-level annotation. LL(1) decidable: peek next token; if "@" consume
; program_annotation, otherwise fall through to param_decl*.
;
; Scoping semantics:
;   resolve(key, S) = S.annotations[key]  if key in S.annotations
;                     program.annotations[key]  otherwise
; Program-level annotations act as defaults; schedule-level annotations override.
; Same keyword may appear at both levels (e.g. @reinforcer at program level as
; default, overridden on a specific schedule in a choice procedure).

program_annotation ::= annotation

param_decl    ::= param_name "=" value
param_name    ::= "LH" | "LimitedHold"
                | "COD" | "ChangeoverDelay"
                | "FRCO" | "FixedRatioChangeover"
                | "BO"  | "Blackout"
                | "RD"  | "ReinforcementDelay"

binding       ::= "let" ident "=" schedule

; === Schedule expressions ===

schedule      ::= base_schedule (("LH" | "LimitedHold") ws? value)?
                                 (("TO" | "Timeout") "(" timeout_args ")")?
                                 ("ResponseCost" "(" response_cost_args ")")?
; LH is a temporal availability property of the schedule it follows.
; AST: absorbed into the inner node's optional `limitedHold` / `limitedHoldUnit` properties.
; No separate LimitedHold wrapper node is emitted.
;
; Semantic constraint (LH_ON_COMPOUND):
;   LH applied to a Compound or Modifier (except DRModifier) → SemanticError.
;   In the behavioral literature, LH is always written as a property of
;   individual (leaf) schedules, not of compound arrangements.
;   "Conc(VI 30-s LH 5-s, VI 60-s LH 10-s)" — not "Conc(VI 30-s, VI 60-s) LH 5-s".
;   Use per-component LH or program-level `LH = Xs` default propagation instead.
;
; Permitted targets: Atomic, Special, DRModifier, SecondOrder, TrialBased.
; DRModifier is permitted because DRL LH is an established paradigm (Kramer & Rilling, 1970).
;
; TO (Timeout) is a response-contingent removal of reinforcement availability
; (negative punishment; Leitenberg, 1965). Postfix position follows LH.
; AST: absorbed into the inner node's optional `timeout` property (object).
; No separate Timeout wrapper node is emitted.
;
; Semantic constraint (TO_ON_COMPOUND):
;   TO applied to a Compound → SemanticError. Apply per-component instead.
;   "Conc(VI 30-s TO(...), VI 60-s)" — not "Conc(VI 30-s, VI 60-s) TO(...)".
; Semantic constraint (TO_ON_AVERSIVE):
;   TO on AversiveSchedule → SemanticError. Timeout from avoidance is incoherent.
; Semantic constraint (TO_ON_EXT):
;   TO applied to EXT → Linter WARNING (not an error). EXT never produces
;   reinforcement, so removing reinforcement availability has no effect.
;
; Permitted targets: Atomic, Special, DRModifier, SecondOrder.
; Combined with LH: `FI 30-s LH 10-s TO(duration=30-s, reset_on_response=true)` is valid.
;
; ResponseCost is a response-contingent removal of a conditioned reinforcer
; (negative punishment; Kazdin, 1972; Weiner, 1962). Postfix position follows TO.
; AST: absorbed into the inner node's optional `responseCost` property (object).
; No separate ResponseCost wrapper node is emitted. Declarative only — balance
; tracking, bankruptcy, and dynamic token state are the responsibility of
; the recording/execution layer, not the DSL (static, non-Turing-complete).
;
; Semantic constraint (RC_ON_COMPOUND):
;   ResponseCost applied to a Compound → SemanticError. Apply per-component instead.
;   "Conc(VI 30-s ResponseCost(amount=1), VI 60-s)" —
;   not "Conc(VI 30-s, VI 60-s) ResponseCost(amount=1)".
;
; Permitted targets: Atomic, Special, DRModifier, SecondOrder, AversiveSchedule.
; RC on AversiveSchedule is permitted: the grammar does not exclude combining
; shock-based avoidance with point-loss contingencies. Whether such combinations
; are empirically meaningful is a research question, not a syntactic constraint.
; Combined with LH/TO: `FI 30-s LH 10-s TO(duration=30-s, reset_on_response=true)
;   ResponseCost(amount=1)` is syntactically valid.

base_schedule ::= atomic_or_second
                | compound
                | modifier
                | aversive_schedule
                | ident
                | "(" schedule ")"

; === Atomic and second-order schedules ===
;
; Second-order: FR5(FI30) = "5 completions of FI30 produce reinforcement"
; Resolved by LL(2): parse atomic, then peek for "(".

atomic_or_second ::= parametric_atomic ("(" simple_schedule ")")?
                   | "EXT"
                   | "CRF"

parametric_atomic ::= dist domain ws? value

simple_schedule   ::= parametric_atomic

; === Atomic components ===

dist          ::= "F" | "V" | "R"
domain        ::= "R" | "I" | "T"
ws            ::= " "+
value         ::= number (time_sep? time_unit)?
time_sep      ::= "-" | ws
time_unit     ::= "s" | "sec" | "ms" | "min"
number        ::= [0-9]+ ("." [0-9]+)?

; Time unit disambiguation:
;   After a number in a value position, time_unit literals are parsed
;   greedily regardless of separator form. All of the following are
;   equivalent: 30-s, 30s, 30 s, 30-sec, 30sec, 30 sec, 30-min, 30 min.
;
;   LL(2) decision: after number, peek at next non-ws token.
;   If it is one of {s, sec, ms, min} or "-", consume as time_unit.
;   Otherwise, value production ends at the bare number.
;
;   Consequence: time_unit literals (s, sec, ms, min) are contextually
;   reserved — they cannot be used as identifier names in let-bindings
;   if they would appear immediately after a number in value position.
;   In practice this is not a meaningful restriction (no behavioral
;   schedule is named "s" or "min").
;
; AST normalization:
;   "sec" is normalized to "s" in the AST (both denote seconds).
;   The AST TimeUnit enum is {"s", "ms", "min"} — "sec" does not
;   appear in the AST. Conformant parsers MUST normalize on output.

; === Identifiers ===
;
; Must begin with lowercase letter or underscore.
; Lexically disjoint from all DSL keywords (uppercase-initial).

ident         ::= [a-z_] [a-zA-Z0-9_]*   -- must not match reserved

reserved      ::= "let" | "def"
                | "phase" | "progressive" | "shaping" | "steps" | "use"  -- experiment layer (v2.0)
                | "target" | "approximations" | "method"   -- shaping_decl metadata (v2.x)
                | "dimension" | "stages"                   -- shaping_decl metadata (v2.x)
                | "percentile_rank" | "percentile_window" | "percentile_dir"  -- shaping_decl metadata (v2.x)
                | "artful" | "percentile" | "staged"       -- shaping method enum (context-sensitive, v2.x)
                | "sessions" | "stable"                   -- phase metadata (v2.0)
                | "no_schedule"                            -- experiment layer: Pavlovian/exposure phase (v2.0)
                | "interleave" | "no_trailing"             -- experiment layer: progressive interleave (v2.x)
                | dist domain              -- FR, VR, RR, FI, VI, RI, FT, VT, RT
                | "EXT" | "CRF"
                | combinator               -- Conc, Alt, Conj, Chain, Tand, Mult, Mix
                | "DRL" | "DRH" | "DRO" | "LH" | "LimitedHold"
                | "RD"  | "ReinforcementDelay"   -- v1.x: reinforcement delay (Lattal, 2010)
                | "COD" | "ChangeoverDelay"    -- changeover delay (Herrnstein, 1961)
                | "FRCO" | "FixedRatioChangeover" -- fixed-ratio changeover (Hunter & Davison, 1985)
                | "BO"  | "Blackout"           -- blackout (Mult/Mix; Reynolds, 1961)
                | "PR" | "Repeat"
                | "hodos" | "exponential" | "linear" | "geometric"
                | "start" | "increment"
                | "Sidman" | "SidmanAvoidance" -- v1.x: Sidman free-operant avoidance (Sidman, 1953)
                | "SSI" | "ShockShockInterval"
                | "RSI" | "ResponseShockInterval"
                | "Lag" | "length"            -- v1.x: Lag schedule (Page & Neuringer, 1985)
                | "DiscriminatedAvoidance" | "DiscrimAv" -- v1.x: discriminated avoidance (Solomon & Wynne, 1953)
                | "CSUSInterval" | "ITI" | "mode"
                | "ShockDuration" | "MaxShock"
                | "fixed" | "escape"          -- da_mode values
                | "TO" | "Timeout"             -- timeout (Leitenberg, 1965)
                | "duration" | "reset_on_response" | "contingent_response"  -- TO keyword args
                | "true" | "false"             -- boolean literals (TO reset_on_response)
                | "ResponseCost"               -- response cost (Weiner, 1962; Kazdin, 1972)
                | "amount" | "unit"            -- ResponseCost keyword args (note: "amount" also in adj_target)
                | "Overlay"                   -- v1.x: punishment overlay combinator
                | "target" | "changeover" | "all"  -- Overlay target kw_arg
                | "PUNISH"                    -- response-class-specific punishment (Conc kw_arg)
                | "Interpolate" | "Interp"   -- v1.x: interpolated schedule (Ferster & Skinner, 1957)
                | "count" | "onset"          -- interpolate keyword argument names
                | "Pctl"                      -- Core-Stateful: percentile schedule (Platt, 1973)
                | "IRT" | "latency" | "duration" | "force" | "rate"  -- pctl_target values
                | "window" | "dir"            -- pctl keyword argument names
                | "below" | "above"           -- pctl_dir values
                | "Adj" | "Adjusting"         -- Core-Stateful: adjusting schedule (Blough, 1958; Mazur, 1987)
                | "delay" | "ratio" | "amount"  -- adj_target values
                | "step" | "min" | "max"      -- adj keyword argument names (note: "start" already reserved by PR)
                | "Interlock" | "Interlocking"  -- Core-Stateful: interlocking schedule (Ferster & Skinner, 1957)
                | "R0"                          -- interlock initial ratio (note: "T" is already domain; context-dependent reserved)

; === Compound schedules ===
;
; Keyword arguments follow all positional (schedule) arguments.
; Two forms:
;   1. Scalar:      COD=2s, FRCO=5, BO=5s
;   2. Directional: COD(1->2)=2s, COD(rich->lean)=5s
;
; LL(2) parseable:
;   - kw_name "=" → scalar form
;   - kw_name "(" → directional form
;   - ident "=" in positional position → keyword (not schedule); LL(2) on "="
;
; Parser accepts both forms syntactically; semantic pass validates per-combinator:
;   - Conc: COD (scalar or directional), FRCO (scalar only), PUNISH (punish_directive).
;     Mult/Mix: BO (scalar).
;     Overlay: `target` only (overlay_kw_arg). Others: keyword args → SemanticError.
;   - Directional form: valid for COD on Conc only. Other kw_names with
;     directional form → SemanticError (INVALID_DIRECTIONAL_KW).
;   - Overlay: exactly 2 positional components (baseline + punisher). Semantic
;     constraint enforces this. `target=changeover` narrows punishment to
;     changeover responses only (Todorov, 1971); `target=all` (default) targets
;     all responses.
;   - overlay_kw_arg: "target" "=" → distinct from kw_name "=" (target ∉ kw_name).
;   - punish_directive: "PUNISH" "(" → distinct from kw_name "(" (PUNISH ∉ kw_name).
;     Value is a schedule expression (vs value expression for scalar/directional).

compound      ::= combinator "(" arg_list ")"
                | interpolate
combinator    ::= "Conc" | "Alt" | "Conj"
                | "Chain" | "Tand"
                | "Mult" | "Mix"
                | "Overlay"
arg_list      ::= positional_args ("," keyword_arg)*
positional_args ::= schedule ("," schedule)+   -- minimum 2 positional components
keyword_arg   ::= scalar_kw_arg | directional_kw_arg | overlay_kw_arg | punish_directive
scalar_kw_arg ::= kw_name "=" value
directional_kw_arg ::= kw_name "(" dir_ref "->" dir_ref ")" "=" value
dir_ref       ::= number | ident
kw_name       ::= "COD" | "ChangeoverDelay"
                 | "FRCO" | "FixedRatioChangeover"
                 | "BO" | "Blackout"

; Overlay-specific keyword argument: response-class targeting.
; LL(2): "target" "=" → overlay_kw_arg. "target" is not in kw_name,
; so no ambiguity with scalar_kw_arg.
overlay_kw_arg ::= "target" "=" target_value
target_value   ::= "changeover" | "all"

; Response-class-specific punishment directive (Conc-only).
; Value is a `schedule` expression (unlike scalar_kw_arg which takes `value`).
; LL(2): "PUNISH" "(" → punish_directive. "PUNISH" is not in kw_name,
; so no ambiguity with directional_kw_arg.
;
; References:
;   Todorov (1971) — changeover punishment in concurrent schedules.
;   de Villiers (1980) — subtractive model of punishment on conc VI VI.
;   Critchfield, Paletz, MacAleese, & Newland (2003) — human punishment choice.
punish_directive ::= "PUNISH" "(" punish_target ")" "=" schedule
punish_target    ::= "changeover"
                   | dir_ref "->" dir_ref       -- directional (L→R etc.)
                   | dir_ref                    -- all responses on a specific component

; Interpolated schedule (Ferster & Skinner, 1957):
;   A block of reinforcements on one schedule is inserted into a background
;   of another schedule. F&S notation: "FI 15 inter FI 1".
;   Semantically distinct from all other combinators:
;     - Chain/Tand: sequential completion (no return to first)
;     - Mult/Mix: repeated alternation (not one-shot insertion)
;     - Overlay: concurrent punishment (not temporal insertion)
;   Non-commutative: first arg = background, second arg = inserted block.
;
;   Parameters:
;     count (required): number of reinforcements during inserted block.
;       Integer, no time unit. Must be > 0.
;     onset (optional): time on background before insertion begins.
;       Time value with unit. Must be > 0. Omission → Linter WARNING.
;
; Reference: Ferster, C. B., & Skinner, B. F. (1957). Schedules of
;   reinforcement. Appleton-Century-Crofts. pp. 643-654.

interpolate   ::= ("Interpolate" | "Interp") "(" schedule "," schedule
                  ("," interp_kw_arg)+ ")"

interp_kw_arg ::= "count" "=" number
                | "onset" "=" value

; === Modifiers ===

modifier      ::= dr_mod | pr_mod | repeat | lag_mod
                | pctl_mod                    -- Core-Stateful: see schema/core-stateful/grammar.ebnf

; Note: adj_schedule (Core-Stateful) extends base_schedule, not modifier.
; See schema/core-stateful/grammar.ebnf §2.

dr_mod        ::= ("DRL" | "DRH" | "DRO") ws? value

pr_mod        ::= "PR" "(" pr_opts ")"                   ; explicit: PR(hodos), PR(linear, increment=5)
                | "PR" ws? number                        ; shorthand: PR 5 → linear, start=5, increment=5
                                                         ;   Jarmolowicz & Lattal (2010, The Behavior Analyst)
pr_opts       ::= pr_step ("," pr_param)*
pr_step       ::= "hodos" | "exponential" | "linear" | "geometric"
pr_param      ::= "start" "=" number
                | "increment" "=" number
                | "ratio" "=" number

repeat        ::= "Repeat" "(" number "," schedule ")"

; Lag schedule (Page & Neuringer, 1985). Reinforce the current response
; (or response sequence) if it differs from each of the previous n responses.
; "n" is positional, matching literature notation ("Lag 5", "Lag 10").
; "length" is an optional keyword argument for sequence length. Default = 1
; (individual response unit, as used in applied verbal-behavior research).
; Page & Neuringer (1985) used length = 8 (2-key 8-peck sequences).
;
; Reference: Page, S., & Neuringer, A. (1985). Variability is an operant.
;   Journal of Experimental Psychology: Animal Behavior Processes, 11(3),
;   429-452. https://doi.org/10.1037/0097-7403.11.3.429
;
; LL(1) after LAG_KW: peek NUM → shorthand, LPAREN → parenthesized.
; Proof: spec/en/core/ll2-proof.md §5.6 (D7).

lag_mod       ::= "Lag" ws? number                              -- shorthand: Lag 5
                | "Lag" "(" number ("," lag_kw_arg)* ")"        -- parenthesized: Lag(5, length=8)

lag_kw_arg    ::= "length" "=" number

; === Timeout (v2.0) ===
;
; Timeout: response-contingent removal of reinforcement availability
; (negative punishment; Leitenberg, 1965). Postfix on schedule expressions.
;
; Two required parameters (no defaults — same design philosophy as MISSING_COD):
;   - duration: how long the timeout period lasts
;   - reset_on_response: whether responses during TO restart the timer
;     (resetting TO ≈ DRO with opposite consequence polarity; see defaults.md)
; One conditionally required parameter:
;   - contingent_response: which response class triggers TO (multi-operandum only)
;
; Reference:
;   Leitenberg, H. (1965). Is time-out from positive reinforcement an aversive
;     event? *Psychological Bulletin*, 64(6), 428-441.
;     https://doi.org/10.1037/h0022657
;   Solnick, J. V., Rincover, A., & Peterson, C. R. (1977). Some determinants
;     of the reinforcing and punishing effects of timeout. *JABA*, 10(3), 415-424.
;     https://doi.org/10.1901/jaba.1977.10-415

timeout_args  ::= timeout_kwarg ("," timeout_kwarg)*
timeout_kwarg ::= "duration" "=" value
                | "reset_on_response" "=" boolean
                | "contingent_response" "=" label_ref

boolean       ::= "true" | "false"
label_ref     ::= ident | number          -- operandum index (1-based) or let-bound name

; === Response Cost ===
;
; Response cost: response-contingent removal of a conditioned reinforcer
; (negative punishment; Kazdin, 1972; Weiner, 1962). Postfix on schedule
; expressions, following LH and TO.
;
; Declarative structure only:
;   - amount (required): magnitude of conditioned reinforcer removed per response
;   - unit (optional): label for the conditioned reinforcer; default "token"
;
; The DSL does NOT track token balance, bankruptcy, or bank-account state.
; Balance arithmetic is a recording-layer concern, outside the static
; contingency structure described here.
;
; References:
;   Weiner, H. (1962). Some effects of response cost upon human operant
;     behavior. *JEAB*, 5(2), 201-208. https://doi.org/10.1901/jeab.1962.5-201
;   Weiner, H. (1963). Response cost and the aversive control of human
;     operant behavior. *JEAB*, 6(3), 415-421.
;     https://doi.org/10.1901/jeab.1963.6-415
;   Kazdin, A. E. (1972). Response cost: The removal of conditioned
;     reinforcers for therapeutic change. *Behavior Therapy*, 3(4), 533-546.
;     https://doi.org/10.1016/S0005-7894(72)80001-7
;   Hackenberg, T. D. (2009). Token reinforcement: A review and analysis.
;     *JEAB*, 91(2), 257-286. https://doi.org/10.1901/jeab.2009.91-257

response_cost_args  ::= rc_kwarg ("," rc_kwarg)*
rc_kwarg            ::= "amount" "=" number
                      | "unit" "=" string_literal

; === Aversive schedules (v1.x) ===
;
; Schedules in which the consequent stimulus is aversive and the contingency
; structure differs from the F/V/R × R/I/T reinforcement matrix.
;
; v1.x introduces two aversive primitives:
;   1. Sidman free-operant avoidance (Sidman, 1953)
;   2. Discriminated avoidance (Solomon & Wynne, 1953)
;
; Punishment overlay is handled via the Overlay combinator (compound section).
; Future extensions (additive): escape as standalone primitive.
;
; Sidman free-operant avoidance (Sidman, 1953):
;   Two temporal parameters with distinct semantics:
;     SSI (Shock-Shock Interval): baseline time between shocks in absence of response
;     RSI (Response-Shock Interval): postponement time triggered by each response
;   Formally: next_shock(t) = max(last_shock + SSI, last_response + RSI)
;
; Reference: Sidman, M. (1953). Two temporal parameters of the maintenance of
;   avoidance behavior by the white rat. Journal of Comparative and Physiological
;   Psychology, 46(4), 253-261. https://doi.org/10.1037/h0060730

aversive_schedule ::= sidman_avoidance
                    | discriminated_avoidance

sidman_avoidance  ::= ("Sidman" | "SidmanAvoidance") "(" sidman_arg ("," sidman_arg)* ")"

sidman_arg        ::= sidman_kw "=" value

sidman_kw         ::= "SSI" | "ShockShockInterval"
                    | "RSI" | "ResponseShockInterval"

; Discriminated avoidance (Solomon & Wynne, 1953):
;   A CS (warning signal) precedes the US (aversive stimulus) by a fixed
;   interval (CSUSInterval). A response during the CS prevents the US
;   (avoidance trial). On failure, the US is either:
;     mode=fixed:  presented for a fixed ShockDuration
;     mode=escape: terminated by a response (optional MaxShock safety cutoff)
;   ITI is measured CS-onset → next-CS-onset.
;
; Reference: Solomon, R. L., & Wynne, L. C. (1953). Traumatic avoidance
;   learning: Acquisition in normal dogs. Psychological Monographs: General
;   and Applied, 67(4), 1-19. https://doi.org/10.1037/h0093649

discriminated_avoidance ::= ("DiscriminatedAvoidance" | "DiscrimAv")
                            "(" da_arg ("," da_arg)* ")"

da_arg            ::= da_temporal_kw "=" value
                    | "mode" "=" da_mode

da_temporal_kw    ::= "CSUSInterval" | "ITI" | "ShockDuration" | "MaxShock"

da_mode           ::= "fixed" | "escape"

; === Comments (line-level, not in BNF productions) ===
;
; "--" begins a line comment extending to end of line.
; Comments are stripped during lexing.

; === Annotations (§4.7 — annotation system, program-scoped closure) ===
;
; Annotations are parsed against an AnnotationRegistry that is provided
; by the receiving program (runtime / interpreter), NOT by the DSL spec
; itself. Within a given program's registry, closure holds: unknown
; annotation names raise a parse error in that program. Across programs,
; registries may differ — this is the mechanism by which 3rd-party
; extensions and opposing theoretical frameworks are supported without
; modifying Core DSL.
;
; Core grammar (this file) remains CFG / non-TC / LL(1)-LL(2) decidable
; regardless of which registry is used. Static verification of Core
; structure (reachability, type consistency) is decidable at the DSL
; level; static verification of annotation names is decidable at the
; program level only.
;
; See spec/ja/design-philosophy.md §4.2 (categories are recommendations,
; not enforced) and §4.3 (category-neutral program equivalence).
;
; Two scoping levels:
;   1. Program-level (program_annotation): appears before param_decl*.
;      Acts as session-wide default. Typical: @species, @strain, @n, @history,
;      @deprivation, @chamber, @hardware, @interface, @clock, @warmup, @algorithm.
;   2. Schedule-level (in annotated_schedule): attached to a schedule expression.
;      Overrides program-level for that expression. Typical: @operandum, @sd, @brief.
;   Some keywords (e.g. @reinforcer) may appear at either level.
;
; Scoping resolution:
;   resolve(key, S) = S.annotations[key]  if key in S.annotations
;                     program.annotations[key]  otherwise

annotated_schedule ::= schedule annotation*
annotation         ::= "@" annotation_name ("(" annotation_args ")")?

; Annotation argument list: supports three forms.
;   1. Positional-only:           @species("rat")
;   2. Positional + keyword args: @chamber("med-associates", model="ENV-007")
;   3. Keyword-only:              @session_end(rule="first", time=60min)
;
; LL(2) decision at the first argument: peek two tokens after "(":
;   - If next is IDENT followed by "=", parse as keyword-only form.
;   - Otherwise parse as positional form (optionally followed by keywords).
; Semantic constraint: within positional form, positional args precede
; keyword args (no interleaving).

annotation_args    ::= positional_form | keyword_only_form
positional_form    ::= annotation_val ("," annotation_kv)*
keyword_only_form  ::= annotation_kv ("," annotation_kv)*
annotation_kv      ::= ident "=" annotation_val
annotation_val     ::= string_literal | time_value | number
                     | annotation_array     ; v0.1: structured values (RFC 2026-04-17)
                     | annotation_object    ; v0.1: structured values (RFC 2026-04-17)
annotation_array   ::= "[" (annotation_val ("," annotation_val)*)? "]"
annotation_object  ::= "{" (annotation_kv ("," annotation_kv)*)? "}"
time_value         ::= number time_unit
string_literal     ::= '"' [^"]* '"'

; Annotation time_value disambiguation:
;   Reuses the same LL(2) strategy as the core `value` production (line 73):
;   after a number in annotation_val position, peek at the next token.
;   If it is a time_unit literal (s, sec, ms, min), consume as time_value.
;   Otherwise, production ends at bare number.
;
;   Note: annotation time_value does NOT support the optional "-" separator
;   that the core `value` production allows (i.e., `time=60-min` is invalid
;   in annotations; use `time=60min`). This avoids ambiguity with negative
;   numbers in keyword argument positions.
;
; AST normalization for annotation time_value:
;   Time values are normalized to a canonical unit (seconds by default)
;   and stored as a number in the Annotation node's params. The original
;   unit is discarded after normalization. Example: `time=60min` → 3600.
;   Programs MAY choose a different normalization convention.
;
; Structured values (annotation_array / annotation_object) — additive
; extension per design-philosophy §8.1 (RFC 2026-04-17):
;   - annotation_array:  [v1, v2, ...]          array literal
;   - annotation_object: {k1=v1, k2=v2, ...}    object literal (uses "=" not ":")
;   Both productions are recursive via annotation_val, allowing arbitrary
;   nesting (e.g., components=[{role="probe", durations=["3s","4s"]}]).
;
;   LL(1) decision: the first token distinguishes each alternative:
;     string_literal    → '"'
;     number/time_value → [0-9]   (existing LL(2) for time_value)
;     annotation_array  → '['
;     annotation_object → '{'
;   All tokens disjoint; parsing remains LL(1) deterministic.
;
;   Object uses "=" (not ":") to match the existing annotation_kv syntax,
;   avoiding two separator conventions within annotations.
;
;   AST representation:
;     annotation_array  → ordered list of annotation_val values
;     annotation_object → map from ident to annotation_val
;
;   Backward compat: the legacy type identifier "array_of_string" in schema
;   format is retained as an alias for "array<string>". Schemas using
;   "array_of_string" (e.g., procedure-stimulus.schema.json relations field)
;   remain valid without modification.

; annotation_name is defined per annotator. The following are the DSL
; project's RECOMMENDED annotators; a program's registry MAY replace,
; extend, or ignore these. Registry composition is program-scoped and
; not enforced by this grammar. See design-philosophy.md §4.2.
;
; Recommended annotators are named to match the JEAB Method section
; headings (Procedure / Subjects / Apparatus / Measurement) 1:1, so that
; a reader can tell the JEAB category from the annotator name alone.
; Programs MAY categorize differently; this list is advisory.
;
;   procedure-annotator   → Procedure   (composed of three sub-annotators)
;     ├── stimulus        : "reinforcer" (aliases: "punisher",
;     │                     "consequentStimulus") | "sd" | "brief"
;     ├── temporal        : "clock" | "warmup" | "algorithm"
;     └── context         : "context"    (v2.0: environmental context for renewal/ABA designs; Bouton, 2002)
;
;   subjects-annotator    → Subjects    : "species" | "strain" | "deprivation"
;                                        | "history" | "n"
;
;   apparatus-annotator   → Apparatus   : "chamber" | "operandum" | "interface" | "hardware" (alias: "hw")
;
;   measurement-annotator → Measurement : "session_end" | "baseline" | "steady_state"
;                                      | "dependent_measure" | "training_volume" | "microstructure"
;                                      | "phase_end" | "logging" | "iri_window" | "warmup_exclude"
;                                        (complete measurement vocabulary)
;
; Extensions (do not map to the four JEAB categories):
;   extensions/social-annotator    : "subject" | "ibc"            (multi-subject; "ibc" = Interlocking Behavioral Contingencies, Glenn 2004)
;   extensions/clinical-annotator  : "function" | "target" | "replacement" (ABA)
;
; See spec/ja/annotation-design.md §3 and §3.7 for the rationale behind this
; 1:1 annotator-to-category correspondence.
;
;
; Annotation aliases: within an annotator, multiple keywords may map to the
; same AST node ("type alias"). Alias relationships are declared by the
; annotator module and do not affect equivalence judgment. See
; spec/ja/annotation-design.md §3.5 for the general principle.

; === Experiment layer (v2.0 — multi-phase experiment description) ===
;
; A file is either a single-phase program (backward compatible) or a
; multi-phase experiment. The parser disambiguates at LL(1): if the first
; non-annotation token is "phase", "progressive", or "shaping", the file is an experiment.
;
; Design rationale:
;   JEAB Method sections describe experiments as sequences of named phases
;   (Baseline → Treatment → Reversal), each with its own schedule, session
;   count, and stability criterion. No existing formal notation unifies
;   within-session contingency description with across-session design
;   structure. The experiment layer fills this gap.
;
; Two output modes:
;   1. Single file, multiple phases: experiment with phase dropdown at runtime
;   2. Multiple files, one phase each: each file is a standard program
;
; Reference: Sidman, M. (1960). Tactics of scientific research. Basic Books.

file          ::= experiment | program     -- backward compatible

experiment    ::= program_annotation* (phase_decl | progressive_decl | shaping_decl)+

; --- Phase declaration ---
;
; A phase is a named program (schedule + metadata). Phase names start with
; an uppercase letter to distinguish them from identifiers (lowercase).

phase_decl    ::= "phase" phase_name ":" phase_body

phase_name    ::= upper_ident              -- Baseline, Treatment, DRA

phase_body    ::= phase_meta* (phase_content | phase_ref | "no_schedule") annotation*

phase_meta    ::= session_spec
                | stability_spec

session_spec  ::= "sessions" ("=" | ">=") number

stability_spec ::= "stable" "(" stability_method ("," stability_param)* ")"

stability_method ::= "visual"              -- experimenter judgment (opaque)
                   | "cv"                  -- coefficient of variation
                   | "relative-range"      -- Costa & Cancado (2012) Criterion 1
                   | "dual-criterion"      -- split-half + visual
                   | "performance"         -- performance threshold
                   | ident                 -- named/custom criterion

stability_param ::= ident "=" (number | number "%" | string_literal | value)

phase_content ::= param_decl* binding* annotated_schedule
                                           -- reuses existing program internals

phase_ref     ::= "use" phase_name         -- reuse another phase's schedule

upper_ident   ::= [A-Z] [a-zA-Z0-9_]*     -- must not match reserved

; --- Progressive Training declaration (syntactic sugar) ---
;
; Progressive training desugars to a sequence of phase declarations, analogous to
; Repeat(n, S) → Tand(S, ..., S). The steps list is a finite literal
; array (no loops, no computation), preserving non-Turing-completeness.
;
; Reference: Sidman, M. (1960). Tactics of scientific research. Basic Books.
;            Ferster, C. B., & Skinner, B. F. (1957). Schedules of reinforcement.

progressive_decl  ::= "progressive" phase_name ":" progressive_body

progressive_body  ::= progressive_steps+ progressive_advance? interleave_decl* phase_meta* param_decl* binding* annotated_schedule
              ; [R-4] progressive_advance injects behavior-dependent step
              ; transition conditions between adjacent generated phases.
              ; At most one progressive_advance per progressive_decl (§69).

progressive_steps ::= "steps" ident "=" "[" number_list "]"
number_list   ::= number ("," number)*

; [R-4] Progressive advance condition
;
; `advance when <condition>` declares a behavior-dependent predicate that
; governs step-to-step transitions within the progressive expansion. The
; condition is evaluated at runtime (not during parse or semantic check);
; the DSL remains non-Turing-complete because:
;   1. The predicate vocabulary is closed (criterion_call with registered
;      metric names, flat all(...) / any(...), manual).
;   2. No recursion, iteration, or computation is introduced.
;   3. Runtime evaluation is the responsibility of the execution engine.
;
; Design provenance: .local/planning_v1/I-13a_SHAPING_ADVANCE_INDUCTION.md
; (EBNF, adversarial review reflection, non-TC verification).
;
; Reference: Eckard, M. L., & Kyonka, E. G. E. (2018). Behavioural Processes;
;            Fernando, A. B. P., Urcelay, G. P., Mar, A. C., et al. (2014).
;            Journal of Neuroscience; Rey, C. N., Thrailkill, E. A., Goldberg, K.,
;            & Bouton, M. E. (2019). JEAB.

progressive_advance ::= "advance" "when" advance_condition

advance_condition ::= "manual"                    ; experimenter-gated (no predicate)
                    | criterion_call              ; single predicate
                    | advance_atom                ; flat all/any compound

; advance_atom is deliberately flat (no recursion): all(...) and any(...)
; take only criterion_call arguments, not other all/any. This constrains
; the logic to CNF/DNF-depth-1 (§R2 of I-13a review).
advance_atom      ::= ("all" | "any") "(" criterion_call ("," criterion_call)* ")"

; criterion_call(metric=..., <comparison_op>=..., window=..., [consecutive=...])
;
; All params are keyword-only. `metric` must resolve to a runtime-registered
; metric name (§70: UNDEFINED_CRITERION_METRIC). The standard registry
; includes: "rate", "irt", "latency", "reinforcers", "avoidance_rate".
; Runtime may register additional metrics; unregistered names raise the
; semantic error at load time.
criterion_call    ::= "criterion" "(" criterion_kw_arg ("," criterion_kw_arg)* ")"

criterion_kw_arg  ::= "metric"      "=" string_literal
                    | "threshold"   "=" threshold_spec
                    | "window"      "=" number window_unit
                    | "consecutive" "=" number

; threshold_spec carries the comparison operator as part of the value.
; e.g., threshold=>=10, threshold=<=0.5, threshold==100
threshold_spec    ::= comparison_op number

comparison_op     ::= ">=" | "<=" | ">" | "<" | "="

window_unit       ::= "sessions" | "blocks" | "trials"

; --- Phase meta placeholder extension (R-4) ---
;
; session_spec is extended to accept a progressive-steps placeholder in the
; number position. This lets session counts vary per step (e.g.,
; `sessions = {s}` where `s = [2, 3, 5, 10, 13]`). Placeholder resolution
; occurs during progressive expansion (same as {x} in schedule templates).
;
; Backward compatibility: the literal-number form `sessions = 5` continues
; to parse unchanged. The extension adds only a new alternative.

session_spec_ext  ::= "sessions" ("=" | ">=") (number | placeholder)
placeholder       ::= "{" ident "}"

; Note: In contexts outside progressive_body, session_spec remains as originally
; declared (literal number only). The placeholder form is accepted only when
; the enclosing production is progressive_body or phase_decl generated from a
; progressive expansion (§75).

interleave_decl ::= "interleave" phase_name [ "no_trailing" ]
                                ; Inserts a clone of the named phase between every
                                ; pair of generated phases (gap block). The named phase
                                ; becomes a "template" — it does NOT appear standalone
                                ; in the resolved PhaseSequence at its declaration position.
                                ; Default semantics: intercalate (a clone is also appended
                                ; after the final generated phase). The "no_trailing"
                                ; modifier suppresses the trailing clone (intersperse).
                                ; Multiple interleave_decl entries are concatenated in
                                ; declaration order to form the gap block; the
                                ; "no_trailing" flag, if present on any entry, applies
                                ; to the entire block (the last occurrence wins for
                                ; readability).

; Progressive placeholders: within a progressive_body, the schedule expression and
; annotation values may contain "{ident}" placeholders that reference a
; steps variable. Placeholders are resolved during progressive expansion.
;
; Expansion rule (E-PROGRESSIVE):
;   progressive Name:
;     steps x = [v1, v2, ..., vn]
;     <meta>*
;     <schedule_template(x)>
;
;     ≡  phase Name_1: <meta>* <schedule_template(v1)>
;        phase Name_2: <meta>* <schedule_template(v2)>
;        ...
;        phase Name_n: <meta>* <schedule_template(vn)>
;
; Multi-variable expansion (E-PROGRESSIVE-MULTI):
;   All steps lists must have identical length.
;   Expansion zips variables pairwise: (x1,y1), (x2,y2), ...
;
; Interleave expansion (E-PROGRESSIVE-INTERLEAVE), default = intercalate:
;   progressive Name:
;     steps x = [v1, ..., vn]
;     interleave R           ; trailing=true (intercalate)
;     <meta>*
;     <schedule_template(x)>
;
;     ≡  [ Phase(Name_1, ..., T(v1)),
;          clone(R, after=Name_1),
;          Phase(Name_2, ..., T(v2)),
;          clone(R, after=Name_2),
;          ...,
;          Phase(Name_n, ..., T(vn)),
;          clone(R, after=Name_n) ]
;
;   With "no_trailing" the final clone is omitted (intersperse).
;   Each clone's label is "<R>_after_<Name>_<i>" (e.g., Recovery_after_DoseResponse_3).
;   Clones are deep copies of the template phase: the template's schedule,
;   criterion, phase_annotations, and phase_param_decls are copied verbatim.
;   The progressive's own annotations and {ident} placeholders are NOT propagated
;   into clones (annotation locality, theory.md §3.3 Definition 16, Property 4).
;
; Multiple interleave_decl entries form a gap block in declaration order:
;   interleave R1
;   interleave R2
;     ⇒ gap = [clone(R1, after=Name_i), clone(R2, after=Name_i)]
;   Result (intercalate): [Name_1, R1_clone, R2_clone, Name_2, R1_clone, R2_clone, ..., Name_n, R1_clone, R2_clone]

; --- Experiment-level semantic constraints ---
;
; 63. phase names: no shadowing. Duplicate phase_name → SemanticError
;     (DUPLICATE_PHASE_NAME). Progressive-generated names (Name_1, Name_2, ...)
;     also must not collide with user-defined phase names.
; 64. use (phase_ref): must reference an already-declared phase (no forward
;     references). Undeclared phase_name → SemanticError (UNDEFINED_PHASE_REF).
; 65. progressive steps: all steps lists within a single progressive_decl must have
;     the same length. Mismatched lengths → SemanticError
;     (PROGRESSIVE_STEPS_LENGTH_MISMATCH).
; 66. progressive steps: lists must contain at least one element. Empty list
;     → SemanticError (PROGRESSIVE_EMPTY_STEPS).
; 67. progressive placeholders: every {ident} in the schedule expression or
;     annotation values must match a declared steps variable. Undefined
;     placeholder → SemanticError (PROGRESSIVE_UNDEFINED_VARIABLE).
; 68. experiment-level annotations (program_annotation before the first
;     phase/progressive/shaping decl) establish defaults for all phases. Phase-level
;     annotations override experiment-level defaults for that phase only.
;     Same scoping semantics as program-level vs schedule-level annotations.
; 69. session_spec: at most one session_spec per phase. Duplicate →
;     SemanticError (DUPLICATE_SESSION_SPEC).
; 70. stability_spec: at most one stability_spec per phase. Duplicate →
;     SemanticError (DUPLICATE_STABILITY_SPEC).
; 71. sessions >= N: N must be a positive integer (≥ 1). sessions >= 0 →
;     SemanticError (SESSION_NONPOSITIVE).
; 72. sessions = N: N must be a positive integer (≥ 1). sessions = 0 →
;     SemanticError (SESSION_NONPOSITIVE).
; 73. no_schedule: declares a phase with no operant contingency. Used for
;     Pavlovian revaluation, context exposure, habituation, or other
;     procedures where no response-consequence relation is programmed.
;     Annotations (e.g., @reinforcer, @punisher, @context) may still be
;     attached to describe stimulus presentations. A no_schedule phase
;     resolves to a Phase node with schedule = null in the AST.
; 74. interleave (E-PROGRESSIVE-INTERLEAVE): interleave_decl.ref must reference
;     an already-declared phase (no forward references). Undeclared/forward
;     reference → SemanticError (UNDEFINED_PHASE_REF; same code as constraint
;     64 because the lookup mechanism is identical to `use`).
; 75. interleave self-reference: a progressive_decl may not interleave a phase
;     declared by itself or by any later progressive_decl in the file. Detected
;     statically by collecting all progressive_decl labels and checking that no
;     interleave_decl.ref equals any later-or-same progressive_decl label.
;     Violation → SemanticError (PROGRESSIVE_SELF_INTERLEAVE).
; 76. template consumption: a phase referenced by ANY interleave_decl is
;     "template-only" — it does NOT appear in the resolved PhaseSequence at
;     its declaration position. Each interleave insertion site receives a
;     deep copy of the template's contents (schedule, criterion,
;     phase_annotations, phase_param_decls) with an auto-generated label
;     of the form "<ref>_after_<progressive-label>_<i>" (1-based). A template
;     phase MAY also be referenced by `use` from other phases — both `use`
;     and `interleave` are pure name-based copies and do not interact.
; 63b. interleave clone labels participate in the standard Constraint 63
;      uniqueness check after expansion. A user-declared phase whose name
;      matches a generated clone label (e.g., user `phase Recovery_after_DoseResponse_3`
;      colliding with a progressive_decl that produces the same label) → SemanticError
;      (DUPLICATE_PHASE_NAME, reused).
;
; --- [R-4] Progressive advance constraints (§77–§82) ---
;
; 77. progressive_advance uniqueness: at most one `advance when` per progressive_decl.
;     Duplicate → SemanticError (DUPLICATE_PROGRESSIVE_ADVANCE).
;
; 78. criterion metric registry: the `metric=` value in every criterion_call
;     must match a runtime-registered metric name. The DSL standard registry
;     includes "rate", "irt", "latency", "reinforcers", "avoidance_rate".
;     Implementations MAY register additional names. Unknown metric →
;     SemanticError (UNDEFINED_CRITERION_METRIC).
;
; 79. advance + fixed sessions conflict: `advance when <non-manual>` is
;     mutually exclusive with an exact-count `sessions = N` session_spec
;     in the same progressive_decl. Rationale: an exact session count implies
;     fixed (time-driven) advancement, while a behavior-dependent
;     advance-condition implies runtime-determined advancement. The two
;     are semantically contradictory. `sessions >= N` is compatible (acts
;     as a minimum-duration constraint that the advance condition layers on
;     top of). Violation → SemanticError (ADVANCE_FIXED_SESSIONS_CONFLICT).
;     Note: `advance when manual` DOES combine freely with `sessions = N`
;     because "manual" cedes control to the experimenter and `sessions = N`
;     documents the observed duration, not a runtime gate.
;
; 80. single-step progressive + advance: a progressive_decl whose steps list
;     contains exactly one element combined with `advance when <predicate>`
;     is semantically vacuous (there is no second step to advance to).
;     Linter WARNING (ADVANCE_SINGLE_STEP). Not an error: useful as a
;     placeholder during incremental development.
;
; 81. placeholder in session_spec: within a progressive_body (or a phase
;     generated by progressive expansion), `sessions = {ident}` or
;     `sessions >= {ident}` must reference a declared steps variable.
;     Undefined placeholder → SemanticError (PROGRESSIVE_UNDEFINED_VARIABLE;
;     same code as §67). Outside a progressive context, the placeholder form
;     is not permitted → ParseError.
;
; 82. manual alternative: `advance when manual` declares experimenter-gated
;     advancement. No predicate is evaluated at runtime; the experimenter
;     is responsible for deciding when to advance (typically via external
;     signal to the execution engine). Non-TC guarantee is preserved because
;     the DSL itself does not loop or branch on any behavioral measure.

; =====================================================================
; --- Shaping declaration (Skinner response shaping, v2.x) ---
; =====================================================================
;
; Within-session response shaping via differential reinforcement of
; successive approximations to a terminal response class. Distinct from
; progressive_decl (across-session parameter progression). Syntactic sugar
; that desugars to a single Phase (for method=artful or method=percentile)
; or to a progressive_decl (for method=staged).
;
; Design provenance:
;   .local/context/ast-completeness-vs-execution-orthogonality.md
;   (AST completeness vs execution orthogonality principle; shaping as
;    under-specified procedure; artful/percentile/staged method taxonomy)
;
; Desugar rules (D-SHAPING):
;
;   shaping Name:
;     target = "X"
;     method = artful                     [default]
;     approximations = ["a1", "a2", ...]  [optional]
;     stable(...)                         [optional; defaults to ExperimenterJudgment]
;
;     ≡  phase Name:
;          @procedure("shape", target="X", method="artful",
;                     approximations=["a1", "a2", ...])
;          CRF
;          [stability_spec | ExperimenterJudgment]
;
;   shaping Name:
;     target = "X"
;     method = percentile
;     dimension = force
;     percentile_rank = 50
;     percentile_window = 20   [default 20]
;     percentile_dir = below   [default below]
;     stable(...)              [required: stability_spec or session_spec]
;
;     ≡  phase Name:
;          @procedure("shape", target="X", method="percentile", dimension="force")
;          Pctl(force, 50, window=20, dir=below)
;          [stability_spec]
;
;   shaping Name:
;     target = "X"
;     method = staged
;     stages = [ S_1, S_2, ..., S_n ]
;     stable(...)              [required]
;
;     ≡  progressive Name:
;          steps i = [1, 2, ..., n]        ; synthetic index
;          [stability_spec]
;          <stages[i-1]>                   ; desugar emits each S_i as a phase
;
; Note: method=staged's `stages` are literal schedule expressions (not
; parameter values). Each stage becomes an independent phase.
;
; Reference:
;   Skinner, B. F. (1953). Science and Human Behavior. Macmillan.
;   Catania, A. C. (2013). Learning (5th ed.). Sloan.
;   Galbicka, G. (1994). Shaping in the 21st century: Moving percentile
;     schedules into applied settings. JABA, 27(4), 739-760.
;     https://doi.org/10.1901/jaba.1994.27-739
;   Platt, J. R. (1973). Percentile reinforcement: Paradigms for
;     experimental analysis of response shaping. In G. H. Bower (Ed.),
;     The psychology of learning and motivation (Vol. 7, pp. 271-296).
;     Academic Press.

shaping_decl  ::= "shaping" phase_name ":" shaping_body

shaping_body  ::= shaping_meta+ phase_meta* annotation*

shaping_meta  ::= target_decl
                | method_decl
                | approximations_decl
                | dimension_decl
                | pctl_rank_decl
                | pctl_window_decl
                | pctl_dir_decl
                | stages_decl

; Required. Terminal response class name. Enforces Galbicka (1994) Rule 2.
target_decl         ::= "target" "=" string_literal

; Optional. Default = artful.
method_decl         ::= "method" "=" ("artful" | "percentile" | "staged")

; Optional metadata (displayed; not executed).
approximations_decl ::= "approximations" "=" "[" string_literal_list "]"

; Required when method=percentile.
; Reuses pctl_target enum from core-stateful/grammar.ebnf §1.
dimension_decl      ::= "dimension" "=" pctl_target

; Required when method=percentile. Integer in [0, 100].
pctl_rank_decl      ::= "percentile_rank" "=" number

; Optional. Default = 20 (Platt, 1973).
pctl_window_decl    ::= "percentile_window" "=" number

; Optional. Default = "below".
pctl_dir_decl       ::= "percentile_dir" "=" pctl_dir

; Required when method=staged. Ordered list of schedule expressions
; (minimum length 2).
stages_decl         ::= "stages" "=" "[" schedule_expr_list "]"

string_literal_list ::= string_literal ("," string_literal)*
schedule_expr_list  ::= annotated_schedule ("," annotated_schedule)*

; === Semantic constraints for shaping_decl ===
;
; 83. shaping target required: every shaping_decl must include exactly one
;     target_decl. Missing → SemanticError (MISSING_SHAPING_TARGET).
;
; 84. shaping method: if method_decl is omitted, defaults to "artful".
;     Explicit method_decl value must be one of {artful, percentile, staged}.
;     Unknown value → SemanticError (UNKNOWN_SHAPING_METHOD).
;
; 85. method=percentile requires all of:
;       - dimension_decl
;       - pctl_rank_decl
;       - phase_meta (stability_spec or session_spec) serving as the
;         phase-change criterion.
;     Missing any → SemanticError (INCOMPLETE_PERCENTILE_SHAPING).
;
; 86. method=staged requires all of:
;       - stages_decl with at least 2 stages
;       - phase_meta (stability_spec or session_spec) applied per-stage.
;     Missing → SemanticError (INCOMPLETE_STAGED_SHAPING).
;
; 87. method=artful: phase_meta is optional. When both stability_spec and
;     session_spec are absent, the desugared phase criterion defaults to
;     ExperimenterJudgment.
;
; 88. percentile_rank range: must be integer in [0, 100]. Out of range →
;     SemanticError (PCTL_INVALID_RANK; same code as core-stateful §P1).
;
; 89. percentile_window positivity: must be integer ≥ 1. Zero or negative
;     → SemanticError (PCTL_INVALID_WINDOW; same code as core-stateful §P2).
;
; 90. duplicate shaping_meta: each shaping_meta kind (target, method,
;     approximations, dimension, percentile_*, stages) may appear at most
;     once per shaping_decl. Duplicate → SemanticError
;     (DUPLICATE_SHAPING_META).
;
; 91. shaping_meta validity for method: shaping_meta declarations must be
;     consistent with the method value.
;       - method=artful  : dimension, pctl_*, stages are forbidden
;       - method=percentile : approximations, stages are forbidden
;       - method=staged  : dimension, pctl_*, approximations are forbidden
;     Violation → SemanticError (SHAPING_META_METHOD_MISMATCH).
;
; 92. empty approximations label: every element of approximations_decl
;     must be a non-empty string. Empty string → SemanticError
;     (EMPTY_APPROXIMATION_LABEL).
;
; 93. stages minItems: stages_decl list must contain at least 2 elements
;     (a single stage is a regular phase, not a shaping). Fewer than 2 →
;     SemanticError (SHAPING_INSUFFICIENT_STAGES).

; === Semantic constraints (enforced post-parse) ===
;
; 1. let bindings: no shadowing, no forward references, top-level only.
; 2. Repeat(n, S) expands to Tand(S, ..., S) [n copies].
; 3. Program-level LH default applies to all leaf base_schedules.
; 4. second-order overall: parametric atomics only (no EXT, CRF).
; 5. second-order unit (v1.0, frozen): simple schedules only (no compounds).
;    Compound inner → INVALID_SECOND_ORDER_UNIT (SemanticError).
;    Rationale: Kelleher (1966), Malagodi et al. (1973), Jwaideh (1973)
;    all use simple-inside-simple; no published compound-inner exists.
; 6. def: reserved keyword, not implemented in v1.0.
; 7. Conc combinator: COD specification is optional (implicit default: COD=0s).
;    Conc without COD (neither expression-level keyword arg nor program-level
;    param_decl) → Linter WARNING (MISSING_COD). Not a SemanticError.
;    COD=0s (explicit) is legal and does NOT trigger the warning.
;    Rationale: COD is procedurally essential (Herrnstein, 1961) but
;    omission is permitted for conceptual/pedagogical use.
; 8. COD/FRCO keyword args: valid on Conc only.
;    BO keyword arg: valid on Mult/Mix only.
;    Other combinators with keyword args → SemanticError (INVALID_KEYWORD_ARG).
; 9. FRCO keyword arg: optional, Conc only. Value is integer (response count).
;    Origin: Hunter & Davison (1985). Pliskoff & Fetterman (1981) used the
;    descriptive term "changeover requirement"; FRCO is the standard abbreviation.
; 10. Keyword arg ordering: must follow all positional schedule args.
;     Keyword before positional → ParseError (KEYWORD_BEFORE_POSITIONAL).
; 11. Duplicate keyword args → SemanticError (DUPLICATE_KEYWORD_ARG).
; 12. Program-level COD/FRCO param_decl applies to all Conc combinators.
;     Expression-level keyword args override program-level defaults.
; 13. BO keyword arg: valid on Mult/Mix only. Optional (unlike COD).
;     Omission of BO → no blackout (immediate component transition).
;     BO=0 is legal (explicit no-blackout; equivalent to omission).
;     Value must include a time unit (e.g., BO=5s, BO=2000ms).
; 14. Program-level BO param_decl applies to all Mult/Mix combinators.
;     Expression-level BO overrides program-level default.
; 15. Program-level annotations (program_annotation) establish defaults for
;     all schedule expressions in the program. Schedule-level annotations
;     (in annotated_schedule) override for the attached expression only.
;     Same keyword may appear at both levels.
; 16. Annotations with component-specific parameters (e.g. @operandum with
;     component=N) at program level → SemanticError (PROGRAM_ANNOTATION_COMPONENT).
;     Component indexing requires schedule-level context.
; 17. Sidman primitive: both SSI and RSI are REQUIRED parameters.
;     Missing either (or specifying only one) → SemanticError (MISSING_SIDMAN_PARAM).
;     There is no default value — the procedure is undefined without both parameters.
; 18. Sidman primitive: SSI and RSI values MUST include a time unit (s/ms/min).
;     Dimensionless values → SemanticError (SIDMAN_TIME_UNIT_REQUIRED).
;     Rationale: Sidman's procedure is intrinsically temporal; a dimensionless
;     interval is procedurally meaningless.
; 19. Sidman primitive: SSI > 0 and RSI > 0 (both strictly positive).
;     Zero or negative values → SemanticError (SIDMAN_NONPOSITIVE_PARAM).
; 20. Sidman primitive: RSI <= SSI is recommended.
;     RSI > SSI → Linter WARNING (RSI_EXCEEDS_SSI). Not a SemanticError.
;     Rationale: If RSI > SSI, the response postponement effect is subsumed
;     by the SSI baseline timer — responses never actually postpone shocks
;     (Sidman, 1953; Hineline, 1977). Useful to flag this as likely user error.
; 21. Duplicate Sidman parameter keywords → SemanticError (DUPLICATE_SIDMAN_PARAM).
;     E.g., `Sidman(SSI=20s, SSI=30s)` → error. Verbose alias does not count as
;     duplicate: `Sidman(SSI=20s, ShockShockInterval=30s)` → error (same parameter).
; 22. Lag modifier: n must be a non-negative integer.
;     `Lag 5.5` or `Lag -1` → SemanticError (LAG_INVALID_N_VALUE).
;     `Lag 0` is legal and is semantically equivalent to CRF (no variability
;     requirement, all responses reinforced).
; 23. Lag modifier: n must NOT carry a time unit.
;     `Lag 5s` → SemanticError (LAG_UNEXPECTED_TIME_UNIT).
;     Rationale: Lag is categorical / sequence-based (Page & Neuringer, 1985);
;     no established variant uses a time dimension.
; 24. Lag modifier: length must be a positive integer (>= 1) if specified.
;     Omission implies length = 1 (individual response as the unit).
;     `Lag(5, length=0)` or `Lag(5, length=-1)` → SemanticError (LAG_INVALID_LENGTH).
; 25. Lag modifier: large n values (> 50) trigger Linter WARNING (LAG_LARGE_N).
;     Historical research (Page & Neuringer, 1985; Neuringer, 2002) typically
;     uses n <= 50. Very large n approaches "novel response only" semantics,
;     which may be the user's intent but is worth flagging.
; 26. Lag modifier: duplicate keyword arguments → SemanticError
;     (DUPLICATE_LAG_KW_ARG). E.g., `Lag(5, length=4, length=8)` → error.
; 27. DiscriminatedAvoidance: CSUSInterval, ITI, and mode are REQUIRED.
;     Missing any → SemanticError (MISSING_DA_PARAM).
; 28. DiscriminatedAvoidance: CSUSInterval, ITI, ShockDuration, and MaxShock
;     values MUST include a time unit. Dimensionless → SemanticError
;     (DA_TIME_UNIT_REQUIRED).
; 29. DiscriminatedAvoidance: all temporal parameter values must be strictly
;     positive. Zero or negative → SemanticError (DA_NONPOSITIVE_PARAM).
; 30. DiscriminatedAvoidance: mode=fixed REQUIRES ShockDuration.
;     mode=fixed without ShockDuration → SemanticError (MISSING_SHOCK_DURATION).
; 31. DiscriminatedAvoidance: mode-dependent parameter exclusion.
;     mode=fixed with MaxShock → SemanticError (INVALID_PARAM_FOR_MODE).
;     mode=escape with ShockDuration → SemanticError (INVALID_PARAM_FOR_MODE).
; 32. DiscriminatedAvoidance: unknown mode value → SemanticError (DA_INVALID_MODE).
;     Only "fixed" and "escape" are valid.
; 33. DiscriminatedAvoidance: ITI must be > CSUSInterval.
;     ITI <= CSUSInterval → SemanticError (DA_ITI_TOO_SHORT).
;     Rationale: ITI is CS-onset → next-CS-onset; if ITI <= CSUSInterval the
;     next trial starts before or at US onset, making the trial structure
;     incoherent (Solomon & Wynne, 1953).
; 34. DiscriminatedAvoidance: duplicate keyword args → SemanticError
;     (DUPLICATE_DA_PARAM). Verbose alias does not bypass: "DiscriminatedAvoidance"
;     and "DiscrimAv" are the same primitive.
; 35. Overlay combinator: exactly 2 positional components.
;     Fewer than 2 → ParseError (compound requires 2+).
;     More than 2 → SemanticError (OVERLAY_REQUIRES_TWO).
; 36. Overlay combinator: only `target` keyword arg is permitted.
;     Any other keyword arg (COD, FRCO, BO, etc.) → SemanticError
;     (INVALID_KEYWORD_ARG).
; 36a. overlay_kw_arg (`target`) is valid on Overlay ONLY.
;      `target` on any other combinator → SemanticError (INVALID_OVERLAY_TARGET).
; 36b. `target=changeover`: the first positional component (baseline) MUST be
;      a Conc combinator. Non-Conc baseline → SemanticError (TARGET_REQUIRES_CONC).
;      Rationale: changeover is defined as switching between concurrent components;
;      a single-schedule baseline has no changeover to target (Todorov, 1971).
; 36c. `target=all`: all responses in the baseline are targeted. This is the
;      implicit default when `target` is omitted. Explicitly specifying
;      `target=all` produces the same AST as omission (backward-compatible).
; 36d. Duplicate `target` keyword → SemanticError (DUPLICATE_KEYWORD_ARG).
;      E.g., `Overlay(Conc(VI30s, VI60s), FR1, target=changeover, target=all)`
;      → error.
; 37. Interpolate combinator: exactly 2 positional schedule components.
;     First = background schedule, second = inserted block schedule.
;     Non-commutative: Interpolate(A, B) ≠ Interpolate(B, A).
;     Fewer than 2 → ParseError. More than 2 → SemanticError (INTERPOLATE_REQUIRES_TWO).
; 38. Interpolate combinator: count keyword arg is REQUIRED.
;     Missing count → SemanticError (MISSING_INTERPOLATE_COUNT).
;     count must be a positive integer (> 0), no time unit.
;     count=0 → SemanticError (INTERPOLATE_NONPOSITIVE_COUNT).
;     count with time unit (e.g. count=5s) → SemanticError (INTERPOLATE_COUNT_TIME_UNIT).
; 39. Interpolate combinator: onset keyword arg is OPTIONAL.
;     If specified, must include time unit and be > 0.
;     onset without time unit → SemanticError (INTERPOLATE_ONSET_TIME_UNIT_REQUIRED).
;     onset <= 0 → SemanticError (INTERPOLATE_NONPOSITIVE_ONSET).
;     Omission of onset → Linter WARNING (MISSING_INTERPOLATE_ONSET).
;     Rationale: onset is procedurally essential (when does the insertion occur?)
;     but omission is permitted for conceptual/pedagogical use (same pattern as COD for Conc).
; 40. Interpolate combinator: duplicate keyword args → SemanticError
;     (DUPLICATE_INTERPOLATE_KW_ARG). E.g., count=5, count=10 → error.
; 41. Time-based schedules: time unit omission triggers Linter WARNING
;     (MISSING_TIME_UNIT). Not a SemanticError.
;     Applies to:
;       (a) Interval/Time domain atomic schedules: `FI 30`, `VT 60`, etc.
;       (b) DR modifiers (DRL, DRH, DRO): `DRL 5`, `DRH 2`, `DRO 10`, etc.
;           DR modifiers operate on IRT (inter-response time), which is an
;           intrinsically temporal dimension.
;     Does NOT apply to:
;       - Ratio domain (`FR 5`, `VR 10`) — dimensionless.
;       - Lag modifier (`Lag 5`) — categorical/sequence-based, not temporal.
;     Examples:
;       `FI 30` or `VT 60` without s/ms/min → WARNING.
;       `FI 30s` or `VT 60ms` (explicit unit) → no warning.
;       `DRL 5` without s/ms/min → WARNING.
;       `DRL 5s` (explicit unit) → no warning.
;     Rationale: In JEAB Method sections, "FI 30" or "DRL 5" without a time
;     unit would prompt a reviewer to ask for clarification. Procedural
;     reproducibility requires explicit temporal units. Same design philosophy
;     as MISSING_COD (constraint 7) and SIDMAN_TIME_UNIT_REQUIRED
;     (constraint 18).
; 42. RD (ReinforcementDelay) param_decl: value MUST include a time unit
;     (s/ms/min). Dimensionless values → SemanticError (RD_TIME_UNIT_REQUIRED).
;     Rationale: reinforcement delay is intrinsically temporal.
; 43. RD param_decl: value must be non-negative (≥ 0).
;     Negative values → SemanticError (RD_NEGATIVE_VALUE).
;     RD=0s is legal (explicit immediate delivery, no linter warning).
; 44. Program-level RD param_decl is a session-wide directive: the runtime
;     imposes the specified delay between any schedule satisfaction event and
;     consequence delivery. Unlike LH and COD, RD has NO expression-level
;     syntax — it is a param_decl only.
;     Rationale: Per-schedule delays are expressed via Tand(S, FT d) for
;     nonresetting delay or Tand(S, DRO d) for resetting delay (Sizemore &
;     Lattal, 1978). Per-alternative delays in concurrent schedules use
;     Conc(Tand(S1, FT d1), Tand(S2, FT d2)). Signaled delays use
;     Chain(S, FT d) (Lattal, 2010). The program-level RD param_decl
;     captures the common case of session-wide apparatus delay (e.g., feeder
;     actuation time) that applies uniformly to all reinforcement events.
; 45. RD param_decl: large delay values (> 30s) trigger Linter WARNING
;     (RD_LARGE_DELAY). Most published delay research uses delays ≤ 30 s
;     (Lattal, 2010). Not an error.
; 46. Parametric atomic schedule: value must be strictly positive (> 0).
;     `FR 0`, `VI 0s`, `RR 0`, `FT 0s`, etc. → SemanticError
;     (ATOMIC_NONPOSITIVE_VALUE).
;     Zero is reserved for EXT (the algebraic zero element with rawValue = 0).
;     Use `EXT` for extinction semantics; use `CRF` (≡ FR 1) for continuous
;     reinforcement. This constraint matches ast.schema.json exclusiveMinimum=0
;     on Atomic.value.
; 47. DR modifier (DRL, DRH, DRO): value must be strictly positive (> 0).
;     `DRL 0s`, `DRH 0s`, `DRO 0s` → SemanticError (DR_NONPOSITIVE_VALUE).
;     Rationale: DRL(irt_min), DRH(irt_max), DRO(omission_time) are defined
;     over ℝ⁺ (theory.md §1.4). A zero threshold collapses the differential
;     contingency — DRL 0s reinforces every response (= CRF), DRH 0s requires
;     IRT < 0 (impossible), DRO 0s requires zero-duration omission (trivial).
;     Use CRF or EXT for degenerate cases.
; 48. PR modifier: start and increment must be strictly positive (> 0).
;     `PR 0` (shorthand), `PR(linear, start=0, ...)`, or
;     `PR(linear, ..., increment=0)` → SemanticError (PR_NONPOSITIVE_VALUE).
;     Rationale: PR with zero start produces FR 0 (nonpositive, see §46).
;     PR with zero increment produces a constant schedule (never progresses),
;     which is better expressed as a simple ratio schedule.
; 49. FRCO keyword arg: value must be a positive integer (≥ 1).
;     `Conc(..., FRCO=0)` → SemanticError (FRCO_NONPOSITIVE_VALUE).
;     This matches ast.schema.json minimum=1 on CompoundParams.FRCO.value.
;     Rationale: FRCO specifies the number of responses required on the new
;     operandum after a changeover (Hunter & Davison, 1985). Zero responses
;     is no changeover requirement, which is the implicit default when FRCO
;     is omitted entirely.
; 50. Directional keyword arg form `kw_name(dir_ref->dir_ref)=value`:
;     valid for COD on Conc only. Other kw_names (FRCO, BO) or
;     non-Conc combinators with directional form → SemanticError
;     (INVALID_DIRECTIONAL_KW).
;     Future: BO may accept directional form for asymmetric blackout.
;     Reference: Pliskoff (1971); Williams & Bell (1999) described
;     asymmetric COD as "VI 60-s → VI 30-s 切替時に 2-s COD".
; 51. dir_ref as integer: 1-indexed. Must be in range [1, N] where N is
;     the number of positional components. Out of range → SemanticError
;     (DIRECTIONAL_INDEX_OUT_OF_RANGE).
; 52. dir_ref as identifier: must resolve to a let-bound name that appears
;     as a positional component of the enclosing Conc. Unresolvable →
;     SemanticError (DIRECTIONAL_IDENT_NOT_FOUND).
; 53. Self-referencing direction: `COD(1->1)=2s` → SemanticError
;     (DIRECTIONAL_SELF_REFERENCE). A component cannot have a COD for
;     switching to itself.
; 54. Duplicate directional: two entries with the same (from, to) pair →
;     SemanticError (DUPLICATE_DIRECTIONAL_KW).
;     E.g., `COD(1->2)=2s, COD(1->2)=5s` → error.
;     Verbose alias does not bypass: `COD(1->2)=2s, ChangeoverDelay(1->2)=5s`
;     → same error (same parameter, same direction).
; 55. Scalar COD + directional COD coexistence: scalar provides base for
;     all unspecified directions; directional overrides specific directions.
;     Resolution: effective_COD(x->y) = directional(x->y) if specified,
;     else scalar_COD.
;     Example: `Conc(VI30s, VI60s, COD=2s, COD(2->1)=5s)` →
;     COD(1->2) = 2s (from base), COD(2->1) = 5s (overridden).
; 56. Directional COD without scalar base: unspecified directions default
;     to runtime COD=0s (consistent with symmetric COD omission behavior).
;     Linter WARNING (MISSING_COD) is NOT triggered if at least one
;     directional COD or scalar COD is present.
; 57. Directional COD values: each value follows the same rules as scalar
;     COD (time unit per constraint 41, value ≥ 0).
; 58. All directional COD values specified for every direction pair with
;     identical values → Linter WARNING (REDUNDANT_DIRECTIONAL_COD).
;     Suggest using scalar form.
; 59. Directional COD is expression-level only. Program-level param_decl
;     does not accept directional form (grammar enforces: param_decl uses
;     scalar value only). Program-level COD provides a symmetric base;
;     expression-level directional COD overrides specific directions.
; 60. Repeat(n, S): n must be a positive integer (≥ 1, no fractional part).
;     `Repeat(1.5, FR5)` → SemanticError (REPEAT_NON_INTEGER_COUNT).
;     `Repeat(0, FR5)` → SemanticError (REPEAT_ZERO_COUNT) [constraint per Issue #34].
;     Rationale: Repeat(n, S) desugars to Tand(S, ..., S) with n copies.
;     A fractional copy count has no behavioral meaning. The grammar's
;     `number` production accepts decimals, so this constraint is post-parse.
;     This matches ast.schema.json type=integer, minimum=1 on RepeatModifier.value.
; 61. PR modifier: pr_start and pr_increment must be positive integers (≥ 1)
;     when specified.
;     `PR(linear, start=1.5, increment=5)` → SemanticError (PR_NON_INTEGER_VALUE).
;     `PR(linear, start=1, increment=2.5)` → SemanticError (PR_NON_INTEGER_VALUE).
;     `PR 0.5` (shorthand) → SemanticError (PR_NON_INTEGER_VALUE).
;     Rationale: PR start and increment represent response counts (ratio
;     requirements) which are inherently discrete. The behavioral pharmacology
;     convention (Hodos, 1961; Richardson & Roberts, 1996) uses integer
;     progressions exclusively. This matches ast.schema.json type=integer,
;     minimum=1 on PRModifier.pr_start and PRModifier.pr_increment.
; 62. limitedHold property must be strictly positive (> 0).
;     `FI30 LH0s`, `VI60s LH0ms` → SemanticError (LH_NONPOSITIVE_VALUE).
;     Program-level `LH = 0s` → same error.
;     Rationale: S LH 0 ≡ EXT (theory.md §2.2.4) — the hold window
;     closes before any response can occur, making reinforcement unavailable.
;     Use `EXT` for extinction semantics. This constraint matches
;     ast.schema.json exclusiveMinimum=0 on limitedHold property.
; 74. Second-order schedule: @brief annotation is recommended.
;     SecondOrder without @brief (neither schedule-level nor program-level)
;     → Linter WARNING (MISSING_BRIEF). Not a SemanticError.
;     @brief(none) (explicit opt-out) is legal and suppresses the warning.
;     @brief("light"), @brief("tone", duration=0.5), etc. also suppress it.
;     Rationale: Brief stimulus (conditioned reinforcer) is a defining
;     independent variable of second-order schedules (Kelleher, 1966).
;     Without brief stimulus, a ratio-overall second-order schedule is
;     procedurally equivalent to a tandem (theory.md §2.11.1). This
;     equivalence may be the user's intent, but the DSL requires explicit
;     acknowledgment via @brief(none) to prevent silent Tand-equivalent
;     arrangements from accumulating in codebases. Same design philosophy
;     as MISSING_COD for Conc (constraint §7).
;     References:
;       Kelleher, R. T. (1966). Conditioned reinforcement in second-order
;         schedules. JEAB, 9(5), 475-485.
;       Goldberg, S. R., Kelleher, R. T., & Morse, W. H. (1975).
;         Second-order schedules of drug injection. Federation Proceedings,
;         34(9), 1771-1776.
;
; --- Timeout (TO) constraints (v2.0) ---
;
; 75. TO: duration keyword arg is REQUIRED.
;     Missing duration → SemanticError (MISSING_TO_DURATION).
; 76. TO: reset_on_response keyword arg is REQUIRED (no default value).
;     Missing reset_on_response → SemanticError (MISSING_TO_RESET_RULE).
;     Rationale: Resetting and non-resetting TO produce qualitatively different
;     behavioral effects. Forcing explicit specification prevents ambiguity.
;     Same design philosophy as MISSING_COD (constraint §7).
; 77. TO: duration value must be strictly positive (> 0) with time unit.
;     duration=0s → SemanticError (TO_NONPOSITIVE_DURATION).
;     duration without time unit → SemanticError (TO_TIME_UNIT_REQUIRED).
;     Rationale: A zero-duration timeout is operationally vacuous.
; 78. TO: duration > mean IRI of the base schedule → Linter WARNING
;     (TO_DURATION_EXCEEDS_IRI). Not a SemanticError.
;     Rationale: If TO outlasts the typical inter-reinforcement interval,
;     the procedure may collapse to near-EXT conditions (Leitenberg, 1965).
; 79. TO applied to EXT → Linter WARNING (TO_ON_EXT). Not a SemanticError.
;     Rationale: EXT never produces reinforcement, so removing reinforcement
;     availability has no operational effect. Likely user error.
; 80. TO applied to Compound → SemanticError (TO_ON_COMPOUND).
;     TO must be applied per-component, not to entire compound arrangements.
;     Rationale: Same as LH_ON_COMPOUND (constraint §6); the target of the
;     timeout must be unambiguous.
; 81. TO applied to AversiveSchedule → SemanticError (TO_ON_AVERSIVE).
;     Timeout from avoidance is semantically incoherent: the aversive schedule
;     operates on shock/US delivery, not on reinforcement availability.
; 82. TO: duplicate keyword args → SemanticError (DUPLICATE_TO_PARAM).
;     E.g., `TO(duration=30s, duration=60s)` → error.
; 83. TO: contingent_response is REQUIRED when the base schedule is a component
;     of a multi-operandum arrangement (e.g., inside Conc).
;     Missing contingent_response in multi-operandum context → SemanticError
;     (MISSING_TO_CONTINGENT_RESPONSE).
;     Rationale: In multi-operandum environments, the response class that
;     triggers timeout must be unambiguous.
; 84. punish_directive (`PUNISH(...)=schedule`): valid on Conc only.
;     PUNISH on any other combinator → SemanticError (INVALID_PUNISH_COMBINATOR).
;     Rationale: Response-class-specific punishment requires the component
;     structure of Conc. Overlay provides a simpler whole-response-stream
;     punishment (see constraint §36 and `target` kw_arg).
;     References: Todorov (1971); de Villiers (1980); Critchfield et al. (2003).
; 85. punish_target `dir_ref`: resolution follows the same rules as directional
;     COD (constraints §51-52).
;     - Integer: 1-indexed, must be in range [1, N] where N is the number of
;       positional components. Out of range → SemanticError
;       (DIRECTIONAL_INDEX_OUT_OF_RANGE, shared with COD).
;     - Identifier: must resolve to a let-bound name that appears as a
;       positional component. Unresolvable → SemanticError
;       (DIRECTIONAL_IDENT_NOT_FOUND, shared with COD).
; 86. punish_target self-reference: `PUNISH(1->1)=FR1` → SemanticError
;     (PUNISH_SELF_REFERENCE). A component cannot have directional punishment
;     for switching to itself (parallel to constraint §53 for COD).
; 87. Duplicate punish_directive: two entries with the same target →
;     SemanticError (DUPLICATE_PUNISH_DIRECTIVE).
;     Examples:
;       - `PUNISH(1->2)=FR1, PUNISH(1->2)=VI30s` → error.
;       - `PUNISH(changeover)=FR1, PUNISH(changeover)=VI30s` → error.
;       - `PUNISH(1)=FR1, PUNISH(1)=VI30s` → error.
;     Directional and component-targeted entries are distinct: `PUNISH(1->2)`
;     and `PUNISH(1)` do not collide.
; 88. punish_target conflict: `PUNISH(changeover)` cannot coexist with any
;     `PUNISH(x->y)` directional entries → SemanticError
;     (PUNISH_TARGET_CONFLICT).
;     Rationale: `changeover` is a shorthand for all changeover directions;
;     mixing it with explicit directions creates ambiguous layering.
;     To punish some directions asymmetrically, enumerate all directional
;     entries instead of using `changeover`.
; 89. Component-targeted punish `PUNISH(n)=schedule` punishes all responses
;     on component n (regardless of source component). Directional `PUNISH(x->y)`
;     punishes only transitions. The two forms may coexist when targets differ.
;     Reference: de Villiers (1980) — per-component punishment on conc VI VI.
; 90. PUNISH value is a `schedule` expression (atomic, compound, modifier, or
;     special). Compound schedules as PUNISH value are permitted; however,
;     nested PUNISH inside a PUNISH schedule → SemanticError
;     (NESTED_PUNISH_DIRECTIVE). The punishment schedule itself cannot contain
;     response-class-specific punishment.
;
; --- Response Cost (RC) constraints ---
;
; 91. ResponseCost: `amount` keyword arg is REQUIRED.
;     Missing amount → SemanticError (MISSING_RC_AMOUNT).
;     Rationale: the magnitude of the removed conditioned reinforcer is the
;     defining quantity of response cost (Weiner, 1962); omission is not
;     meaningful.
; 92. ResponseCost: `amount` must be strictly positive (> 0).
;     amount=0 or amount<0 → SemanticError (RC_AMOUNT_NONPOSITIVE).
;     Rationale: zero magnitude collapses the contingency to no-op;
;     negative magnitude would denote reinforcer addition, which is not
;     response cost but token reinforcement (use `@reinforcer` annotation
;     or a separate schedule).
; 93. ResponseCost: `unit` is OPTIONAL. Default = "token".
;     Rationale: contemporary ABA literature uses "token" almost universally
;     (Hackenberg, 2009); "point" is retained for fidelity to Weiner's (1962,
;     1963) human-operant paradigm. `unit` is a free-form string label and
;     does not affect the contingency structure.
; 94. ResponseCost: applied to a Compound → SemanticError (RC_ON_COMPOUND).
;     Apply per-component instead. Parallel to LH_ON_COMPOUND (§6) and
;     TO_ON_COMPOUND (§80). The target of cost must be unambiguous.
; 95. ResponseCost: duplicate keyword args → SemanticError (DUPLICATE_RC_PARAM).
;     E.g., `ResponseCost(amount=1, amount=2)` or
;     `ResponseCost(unit="token", unit="point")` → error.
; 96. ResponseCost: declaration of the conditioned reinforcer (via
;     `@reinforcer` annotation at program or schedule level) is RECOMMENDED
;     but not required. If no `@reinforcer` annotation appears anywhere in
;     the program and at least one ResponseCost is present → Linter WARNING
;     (RC_WITHOUT_TOKEN_CONTEXT). Not a SemanticError.
;     Rationale: response cost operates on a conditioned reinforcer; an
;     explicit `@reinforcer` annotation makes the removed token's identity
;     self-documenting and aids downstream tooling. Absence is permitted
;     because simple test programs and pedagogical examples may omit the
;     annotation without ambiguity.
;     Limitation: this check does not distinguish primary from conditioned
;     reinforcers. A program declaring `@reinforcer("food")` (primary) and
;     using ResponseCost will not trigger the warning, even though "food"
;     is not a token being removed. Refining this requires a reinforcer-type
;     annotation extension beyond the core DSL.
